The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria: in total they have 29%
The perceptible weakening of both existing parties in the grand coalition and this marked strengthening of right-wing populist parties, led, according to the first provisional results, to Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), within which the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously faltering, has suffered particularly strong losses.
On the contrary, the Union's electoral leader for the future of Austria (BZÖ), the sub-prefect of Kärnten Jörg Haider, is preparing for the triumphant return to national politics.
According to the provisional results, the strongest party in the country remains the socio-democratic (SPÖ) with 29.8% of the vote, but compared to the last elections in 2006 it loses 5.5%.
Even worse went for ÖVP, which loses with 25.6% almost 9% of the vote.
These are the worst results of these two great parties in post-war Austrian history and especially the literally catastrophic result of the popular, who provoked early elections.
Still in early July, when the ÖVP abandoned the coalition, the popular had a considerable advantage in the front of SPÖ in the preferences.
But the voters evidently punished them because they sank the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there have been speculation about the possible resignation of the party president, Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Monterer.
Observers believe they could take place as early as Monday during the extraordinary convocation of the party leadership.
This evolution should perhaps facilitate the path to the increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. towards the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
With regard to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties (FPÖ), they gained 18% and BZÖ 11% in advance, but the socio-democratics simultaneously revealed the concern of another 1999, when the populists agreed with the people of the collective government, (then the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it separated from the BZÖ) which was even a reason for sanctions by the Union
On this evolution evidently plays Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party and assumes a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Green Party also managed to enter Parliament, but it fell slightly, descending among the Austrian political parties from third to fifth place.
No other party has evidently crossed the 4% threshold and has not entered Parliament.
Duel to the death: MP3 players against mobiles
We will recommend how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
From this it is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Despite this, there are many reasons why to get an autonomous reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy yourself an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LP and from the qualitative point of view for this reason there is not even an objective reason.
But if you crowd hard-rock vinyls, jazz or blues on your shelves, you probably dream of a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are the price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, as well as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digesting the market's twenty-wreath headphones.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The duration of the batteries is decided.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than simply read music, but which mobile phones don’t do by mistake either.
There is no other current device as universal as the mobile phone.
Alongside the primary functions, calling and texting, can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe can even navigate.
And if we take into account smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle because no refrigerator can do the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone, and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few mobiles can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simpler ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, do not count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add to it, from time to time, some call, get to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst lasting at a minimum of 9 hours with continuous functionality with a charge.
A further problem exists when you download music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has the universal USB port and in addition not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to make it without adapter for minicards that are not used in mobiles.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a media library sorted by the names of the interpreters, album name, genre, or by user classification.
