The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missed for a long time.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe, we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, ČTÚ also confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regularisation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really start the clash.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100 %.
Instead, mobile telophony operators like to whine about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, also often emphasizes, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities. (It would be difficult to find other frequencies.)
But there is yet another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has brought a considerable lowering of prices, to which traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile in the market, similar voices as similar as we did in Britain resounded.
However, it has been shown that the place for operators like this is there and that they can be truly successful.
After all, we don't have to go very far for example.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete group-target.
In order to actually work, it is enough for many fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually show up at low cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost at least half compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-target not small.
This operator points specifically to men.
“Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, which manufactures this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also say a similar concept in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no chance, say the operators of the mobile network
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have much expectation.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thinking.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything because you do not create any potential competitor.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner you do the better.
We have negotiated repeatedly on this possibility with all Czech operators in the mobile network.
We have already managed to progress in negotiations with some of them," says Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
The unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, around his creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now we don’t believe that in the Czech market there is space for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," he mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefònika O2 press section.
Other operators also use the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-Mobil's press spokesman Martina Kemrová added in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both of you, on which it is possible to continue building."
He adds: "In the T-Mobil network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we will have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather than reaching its 3G license requests.
Adds Miroslav Čepický : "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this is especially the case in the field of sharing expenses and infrastructure.
Let’s consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
The competent authorities -with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby to the decrease in profit.
Why facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against ČTÚ in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidence of public access information from ČTÚ's web pages.
But now just U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The environment of competition from the mobile phone market has been little done enhanced beyond everything with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high-pretension services.
However, the attitude of mobile operators is surprising the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just about the attitude of the ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Great Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, against the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator was implemented.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS External Relations Section, in the answer to our question.
Such a worded statement from the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead, on the part of the office that must defend the interest of consumers and also take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence, arises on its own.
Likewise, the exact price of petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior about this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so he does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for his behaviour in the market.
The tools needed for the opening of the mobile network market for virtual operators are perhaps also lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points .
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach – the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the day logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we don't admit this argument, for ÚOHS it should be at least allerting that three mobile operators proceed so strangely similarly.
At the same time, complaints from those concerned (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Unloading responsibility in ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole matter.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has failed to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the recently passed telecommunications law, despite the fact that, many experts expected the improvement of the situation.
This fact ÚOHS representatives need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done when no one is looking
While without us realizing it, the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators remains, of which there are even some in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile phone services but are only partially public.
Usually it’s about multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator figures as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special pricing offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you talk about, of which we will be interested, we could deal with a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could result in the conclusion of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová replied to the question in question.
But it is somewhat unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of the subjects responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies, that is, they make a significant profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, therefore they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators "
But this should be a strange minimum at ČTÚ.
Plus another issue opens up for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes in front of such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not expensive
As in the text has already been said several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a significant lowering of prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all the countries where the operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - market too small, to the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in these cases, regulatory bodies have intervened in these cases in defense not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then we came to the creation of the first virtual operator and others joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies launch themselves from one to the other all the case as a hot potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will really soon appear with us, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only it could hardly ÚOHS remain unfazed by the refusal (discrimination) of the other data subjects.
And maybe we'll stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with the male or female voice, chorus step and the instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem reviews are Otakar Jeremiáš and Yaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already before he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the solo variations, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the choir, have the clear diction, that the text is well understandable, that they are in harmony" he reported.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first played in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
He gained popularity and people spontaneously made it his own.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of Czechoslavakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the Czech Republic.
