Mark Brown writes: as Guildford's music director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, 9/11) had in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and the choir.
As a member of his music scheme for the municipality, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
They were supposed to be under-21/ under 21, but by the time the Proteus sang his final in 1979, many of us were more than twenty-somethings - we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological being-changing) represented the goodwill of the choir and the ability to deal with everything that music presented to do, both madrigal and Messiaen, without accompaniment or with the whole orchestra.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting, and it was all because of that man's inspiration and the enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely constant through the years.
How often we were told by Tod to "let the music speak for itself."
He had said: "The composer knows what he wants.
There's everything in the music.
So sing it!"
His technique in the use of the wand was absolutely clear and precise, although never dictatorial nor flowery.
Whatever the musical standard, it was increasingly rising.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If you were to appoint knight a conductor it would have been Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he led the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years and more I have covered more than 100 of his concerts and I can honestly say that I have never disagreed with just one of them - and many times inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He hated the conductors who, in his own words, simply "rode around the world one or two well-known workhorses."
He will be missed by so many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your William Woodruff obituary (September 25) specifies that "in 1946 he resumed studying economic history at Oxford and in 1950 he became a researcher in Houblon-Norman... studying at the same time for a degree in science, one in letters and a PhD."
This follows from the Woodruff author's note in Beyond Nab End, but it's not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a university lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham, at that time he completed a PhD thesis on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor J. D. Chambers, and later published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
He spent 1950-51 in the U.S. as a researcher at Houblon-Norman, and in the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he permanently left Nottingham for Illinois.
Because Woodruff chose to cover this part of his career, you don't know.
Profaned Muslim graves as Austria turns right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, to the left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, take part in a rally to present the organization "City against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
