Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer was faced with an audience to which time flew when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and with great doses of humor, recalled how the literary vocation was born in him, derived from the "extraordinary adventure" of the "pleasure of reading" and "of living beyond what I lived"; as he writes in "disciplined way" to make up for the "lack of work"and Alexandre Dumas have influenced his vocation and how "the images of memory" are the basis on which his stories rest.
The Spanish-American novelist acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and know whether books can change people's lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is pure entertainment, an ephemeral experience," Vargas Llosa pointed out, arguing that, on the contrary, it "has effects" and that it "makes people more nonconformist." For this reason he invited the writers to "not give in to frivolity" and to "take responsibility" for their own vocation.
