Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sevillian essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer pays tribute to another equally Seville dancer.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Florence Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a free dance dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of women's empowerment, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in the field of dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have loved to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. It seemed incredible to me."
She supports the dancer: "we do not pretend to tell her whole life, but to gather her spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
Thus, "la danza de la mariposa" suggested to me a guajira, or "the dance of the snake" some tangos.
His dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing is also part of this aesthetic," he explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing again Isabel in one of her shows, as she does in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been her student.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I'm happy because he's agreed to work in my work and I feel very honoured to that."
The set-up also includes the musical and guitar composition such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi of Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal companion of these artists who have always been well-rounded, and who have always had many
In the work there is also in some form the life of this woman who takes place in distant places, especially for that era, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since, habitually, she resided in London.
“I wanted to remember her, because I think she’s one of the women who had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers it and even less considers her work as something of value,” Bayon said.
The show will begin today, at 8.30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega theatre.
