Talking in sleep
Some children speak during the night.
I'm not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a scare, but it doesn't really matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you were told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (each day, once a week, once in the month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night fears, nighttime enuresis (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but it is not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overexcitement situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, shouts, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety such as venting to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the baby before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleepiloquies appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you'd interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's asleep and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check from where such great anxiety in the child results.
