The meeting - Blood is safe again
The Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dott.ssa FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as the Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the re-proposition of a similar disaster.
As Judge Krever was in delay in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was executed by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the reports Gélineau et Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Society of Blood) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started their activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary said.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood draws and field research over the following years, we regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dott.ssa Décary is however convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we absolutely did not know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are adopted.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years now, it has been shown that without a doubt this disease is transmitted by infected blood.
This episode thus showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the same, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the moment in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to a duration of less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people run the risk of receiving infected blood from the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that you will need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of management of the Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood from an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," continues Dott.ssa Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, the Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
"Necessities increase as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer cures, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average makes up only 3% of Quebecers acceptable as donors.
However, all healthy people who are over 18 years of age and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Cases of scarcity are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them and incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that you find it hardly an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of US$297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye globe heart valves, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which operates the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical deviation, blood rich in stem cells abounds that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the inclusion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand every year.
You should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dott.ssa Décary, which describes this practice of taking cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to have access to it", since the Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals of Quebec.
