Free opinion - The Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million-million-on-art libel lawsuit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house with the intention of launching a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a libel lawsuit, but the law.
Without any surprise, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring about ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, to decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the virtually bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal weapons struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gags the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to pronounce on the issue again.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that he would have to present his own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally held with the exchange of views and not with baton shots.
It would therefore have been enough for society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have too much faith in public opinion and misrejects petitions and letters in support of Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his disdain for that same audience is well evident?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word only indicates the handsomely paid lawyers and not the whole of the Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even disparagers have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports Black Canadian authors and publishers does so first because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of gagging (researching the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Nero an ultimatum informing them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the lawsuit brought by Barrack Gold constitutes a direct attack on university freedom of research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in every democratic society.
It denies in block the right to the citation of authentic sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss on uncomfortable topics to the richest companies in the world, on pain of multiple lawsuits, who can?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific norms as the authors of Black Canada do.
He has the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it is not seeking a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, as well as the same public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures that can limit abusive lawsuits.
Operation - bailout for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, yesterday finally came to an agreement on the biggest financial-saving plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been burdening Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
It provides in particular: verifications of its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms that guarantee the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of homes foreclosed for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection of wages paid to managers of protected enterprises.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress in view of an effective agreement on the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said in a statement.
"Every decision has been taken in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the crisis currently underway on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted this way, priceless discomfort and upset would have spilled over into the daily lives of Americans," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new failure on investors.
The agreed time limit corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
After the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, without, however, avoiding expressing their discontent with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular that which will allow owners to keep their domicile and that inherent in wages intended for business executives covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the screen of American TV.
Interviewed on another channel to know if he will vote in favor of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"According to what I've read, this is something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward"
The option of a non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsaless assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that led first to the collapse of mortgage loans at risk ( mortgages) , and then extend to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and result in the freezing of liquidity and the disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in office who screwed up the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems to have come out of that dead end since Democrats agreed that the "toxic" assets of some struggling companies would only be protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone, in Congress, a provision has been added that, if the government were to cope with losses over the course of five years to come due to such a program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which can be added again 100 billion if the president considers it necessary.
The 350 billion payment is expected to be ratified by a further congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shareholdings in the protected companies that will be worth the dividends in case of profit and that he can resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures related to real estate loans and to set limits on remuneration and starting allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the plan's architects would like to submit it to the House of Representatives vote, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, he is still not sure that the green light to their plan will be given.
In fact yesterday there were several votes against the project, both at the Republican and Democratic side.
"Evidently, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituent voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But certainly not take advantage of the taxpayers..
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to draw conclusions and to carefully examine the way forward," he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the world nature of the crisis.
