Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
Blue-eyed beauty was for a long time its ace up its sleeve, for others its weak point.
Had he gotten rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a bewitching smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and evident talent would have expelled him from that circle of powerful consecrated to real sacred monsters.
What a constancy!
Paul Newman, who passed away on Friday, aged 83, on his Connecticut ranch, following lung cancer, remains one of the last icons of American film of the spledge years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of which he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
From mixed couples, magical children are often born.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, the latest quality mark.
Since in him he recognized himself a whole country in love with the safe made man, the fighter of the Pacific War, proud in the fight, who in the early 50's studied dramatic art in Yale, later attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing at the theater, on television and soon in cinema.
That same civil rights militant man was also the racing driver who ranked second to the 24 hours of Mans in 1979, as well as sex symbol, although part of a model couple from 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The shadows of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to the scandals of show-business, of which the mystery will never be completely revealed.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
