The psychology of excess licitating: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have managed to uncover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study that appeared in the journal Science men do not want to fall behind in a race such as eBay's auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system via experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while with the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the game of the auction, where the substantial element is to squirre more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex intensely enters into operation when lost at the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "autogratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the research group's economists carried out a financial pursuit survey.
In this investigation, three groups have licited against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told how much the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they promised that in the case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group instead would receive 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in case of loss at auction.
