Hepatitis: When to contact your doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of these only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver disease caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against the A and B viruses, against the C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots are formed on the skin and white of the eyes, the stools become clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because pathogens sneakily destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
So it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical analysis.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed.
In the world to date, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory test reveals the disease is worth turning to the GP when noticing any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is treatable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
