The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies if not mimic the sensors of the obstacles found in nature?
For example, those of bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets gave the initial strategic starting point to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of collision-resistant systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic miniauto equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own personal oval space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - he explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the field of PR technologies and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the view of the bee.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres apart within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damable and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is considered currently inevitable.
The whole process must mirror what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, higher-energy, lithium-polymer batteries, which means their lifespan is higher than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot must process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
No need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, Nissan predicts, can be installed on production vehicles within 10 years.
Further application possibilities can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
