The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program that means the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the data subject.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox" - writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies make the insurance fee and the amount due in the event of claims subject to the health status of the customer and if they consider the risk not to be too high, they do not take out the insurance.
Some time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily have information from pharmacies about which medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program evinces which diseases he suffers from and in what health condition he is.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that your blood fat level is incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so in addition to paper work there is not much left, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are employable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, is the same as a factor of increased risk, the first two not.
For the request and data processing, separate companies were formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities oblige them to do so even if so far they have not imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies have recently also developed the result of laboratory tests and linked them to the consumption data medicine in order to provide a more precise picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and in parallel the control of usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
Before Congress there is a proposed law giving the authorities supervisory expertise to companies specializing in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the forwarding of data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
