The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, yes, dense links with foreign countries, but which first of all involve the balance sheets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and those families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems basically out of the game or not having much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union that divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects intervention, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when you get to the corners it is only the states that own the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to get things back on track.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose in a similar way.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is moreover in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal with those very unintangible things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that presages a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take matters into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic, proved so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insuffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of countries in the West.
That seems to be increasingly making way, in large sectors of the population, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, undergroundly feeds an ramified but mighty movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "electoral revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and very last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, they are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep strata of Western societies and that the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, agitates potentially to a great extent.
In the face of all this, talking about a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The superglue for walking on walls
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on the walls like Spiderman.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come very close to us.
With a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100 kilogram body glued on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of scholars is an evolution of existing ones using a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that manage to ensure a perfect grip on the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "it easily detaches from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALKING ON THE WALLS? "This material could be useful as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls just like Spiderman? Perhaps yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could be aerospace engineering.
For the moment no superheroes.
The University of Berkeley, California is also looking for a new sticker.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, Californian scholars presented an adhesive formed from microfibers such as hair that self-cleans from dust during movement on a surface to always maintain a perfect grip.
Drugs: never with fruit juices
Beware of grapefruit juice, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, when taken at the same time as some life-saving drugs alter their absorption by amplifying or decreasing their effectiveness as appropriate with serious consequences for health.
To reiterate the risks of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with taking some medicines David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, and from the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia launches a new alarm: just a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice to reduce the absorption of certain life-saving drugs, canceling the beneficial effects and putting the health of patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice had already ended up under indictment because it was believed to be responsible for increasing the effects of some antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antihistamine and neurological medicines to the extent toxic.
The same Italian Medicines Agency had given notice of it in an information bulletin two years ago alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger arising from this mix and to pay attention to what is drunk in case you take drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to experts, even orange juice and apple juice contain substances that inhibit drugs.
Along the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology at the State University of Milan: "These discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various international and national drug agencies that possibly change the information notes of the drugs.
So always read the package leaflets of the medicines you take and if there is anything that is not clear to us, do not be impressed but ask the doctor or pharmacist for clarification", stressed the expert at the Ansa agency.
