Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, cities cancel historic halls
Historical cinemas close in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the suburbs of large multiplexes and the consequent death by consumption of the monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and full of memory "it is as if a friend was lost, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of street and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prize of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a provincial room and nostalgia for a way of living the cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by ANEC, the main association of exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and to pay the biggest price are mainly the theaters in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna is Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost single-sale cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
