When energy is born from the waves, the bigs take the field
It is an exterminated field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the big energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now they try to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of deriving energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70's, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by oil-intended power plants.
That amount would be twice that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And in addition there would be currents and tides.
Colossi to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years later, to bet on marine energy are more and more and among these companies always devoted to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies, and is considering the possibility of cooperating with us,” a company’s spokesperson familiar with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
It is a significant sign, especially considering that in Alaska the United States continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to the Chevron are New York's Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey's Ocean Power to walk the road of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, however unknown in detail, indicate according to observers a rising interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, not least because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as Portuguese or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants being designed, pending only federal approval and part of the energy could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water when there are tides makes the turbine blades turn, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
The Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves the potential of tides right now.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states such as that of New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and expected investments of up to 35 million for 2009.
